\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the warm light of neon orange, Ethan searched his pockets for the some
 small change, but to no avail.
 He rarely needed dimes and pennies when he made his cosmopolitan visits
 to the center of Lagos, but using the jukebox in Loui's bar was such an
 occasion, and even more so a favourite habit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, Ethan was not a rare visitor to Loui's establishment, and most
 would instantly recognise him.
 He was widely known as the Englishman, both to the few locals and the numerous
 extraordinary foreigners that frequented the Metropolitaine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan maintained that he only came for the regularly up-to-date jukebox,
 whilst his tab indicated a thirsty sort of music lover with a certain taste
 for fine malts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Malts such as the unusually fine scotch that Loui kept stashed for the well-off
 or even well-liked customer.
 He had simply decided to thank God there was good scotch to be found in
 a place like Nigeria and even more so in a bar like Loui's.
 To make the realisation even more mind-numbing for Ethan, there was good
 scotch to be found during what the Nigerian government chose to characterise
 as a `crisis'.
 The Metropolitaine's crude and shanty decoration, or more appropriately
 its blatant lack thereof only helped to somehow accentuate that a war was
 going on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A couple of ceiling fans still worked despite what one might expect at first
 sight, barely keeping the air from going stale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was with his usual wide grin that Louis, the proprietor, approached Ethan
 and offered him a penny before bowing slightly, impeccably dressed in a
 striped jacket, white pressed shirt, bowtie and smart pants, an air of
 the thirties Paris about him.
 Ethan accepted the coin gladly and immediately dropped it in the slot,
 while Louis chimed in his blatantly french but not unbearable accent:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Compliments of the house, Capitain.
 The usual? Little ice, double fine scotch?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan smiled wryly and nodded while selecting a song in the jukebox, his
 index finger searching for the correct button to press.
 He pushed `Under my thumb', and turned to reply to Louis before setting
 off to settle in his usual barstool, the bar solely at his disposal at
 that hour:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Very fine scotch.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Nothing but Scotland's finest, Mr.
 Whittmore.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan sat on the barstool, his eyes staring at the glasses and various bottles
 of liquor neatly arrayed and featuring prominently in the shelves behind
 the bar.
 When he next spoke, it was with a feeling of relief:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'd never thought I'd say this, but God bless Nigeria.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis had assumed his proper place behind the bar when he picked up a bottle
 of one of his finest malts from a cupboard below along with a short glass,
 and said smiling wryly while he poured:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm from Guiana though.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ah, and Scotch is from Scotland but it knows no borders.
 Come on then, pour one yourself.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unusually tall, lank bartender complied and picked up a shot glass which
 he filled promptly and raised to a toast:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

To all the thirsty men.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Rolling Stones song had started playing in the background.
 Ethan raised his own glass of scotch and made a toast as well:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

To Mick Jagger and crew.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They both gulped down their drinks in one go.
 Ethan made a slight motion with one hand, indicating the cupboard below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis went through the motions of pouring another glass of scotch and asked
 his regular customer for the past year or so with his usual air of cool
 affection:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How's life treating you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan's tone was lighthearted, almost flippant when he said:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Not sure.
 Better than horseshit? I'm not complaining though.
 Still 'ere, aren't I?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis laughed politely and nodded before replying:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Woe be me if something should happen to you.
 Losing customers, I cannot afford that?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You're not losing me soon enough.
 Keep the scotch coming, and I'll manage.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis let the glass of scotch slide across the wooden bar and looked Ethan
 straight in the eye, his face almost a pale shade of dark under the dim
 candlelight surrounding the bar:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What news from your friends in high places?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan shook his head and made a strange, sour face for a moment.
 He brought the glass to his lips, sniffing the aromas:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Nothing yet.
 It's not easy, you knew that.
 Not to mention there's money involved.
 But it'll take time Louis.
 Your visa isn't exactly top priority.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis shook his head in disappointment, and started polishing a basket full
 of washed glasses.
 His eyes were fixed to the task at hand when he replied to Ethan with a
 mixed feeling of sadness and slight aggravation, his movements lacking
 his usual crispness and finesse:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You said by the end of the month, Englishman.
 Said you knew the `ins and outs', didn't you? Who will keep Insami and
 Wadu off my back, I wonder.
 Make it top priority, can you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan kept wearing the same smile that had won him arguments on innumerable
 occasions, while he kept tapping his fingers to the rhythm of the song
 playing from the jukebox.
 After a short uncomfortable silence, he said to Louis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It must feel like a kick in the nuts, Louis, but remember, I'm doing you
 a favor.
 Take a look around you.
 There's bigger trouble than those two thugs.
 There's a war going on.
 If they do pop up and act like a couple of tough guvs, I'll make sure they
 get one in the sack and lose a couple of teeth each.
 No use worrying about it now.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis looked a bit distraught, his eyes somewhat dull from wariness.
 Ethan tried to change the subject:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

What do you have for me this time? Auchentoshan? Glenfiddich? 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis became his professional self again; he seemed to relax a bit, his
 tense mouth loosening into a tight smile.
 He reached for a tall cupboard with a lock on the handles, and used a small
 key that hung from a chain around his neck.
 He opened the cupboard with small, graceful movements of his hands, as
 if opening an icon or a shrine.
 In it, a dozen bottles of Littlemill sat, dusty and squat, seemingly quite
 authentic seal, cork and all.
 At the sight of the bottles of scotch and the prospect of savouring them
 at his leisure, Ethan's face lit up and his blue eyes seemed for a moment
 to sparkle.
 His voice couldn't contain his enthusiasm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Littlemill? Thirty-two years old, triple distillation.
 Bugger me, oldest malt in Scotland.
 Let me see that bottle.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis complied even though anyone could tell from his face he was quite
 puzzled.
 Ethan was usually interested in the contents, not the labels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Here you go, englishman.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan completely disregarded the bartender's effort at a light-hearted insult
 and studied the bottle's labels with focused interest.
 At length, he nodded appreciatively before adding:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

From Ayrshire, too.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Loui asked with real curiosity while opening the bottle of Littlemill Ethan
 was still clutching like a scepter:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Is that the place for the best scotch?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan let go of the bottle and while Louis put a single cube of ice in Ethan's
 glass, he continued, his expression emanating a scholarly aura:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

'Tis the ancestral birthplace of the greatest scot that ever lived.
 William Wallace.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The name of the famous scottish hero was intoned with reverence and pride.
 It seemed to have no effect on the Guinean bartender who casually asked:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Who is he?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan blinked twice and was taken slightly aback when the name of the greatest
 Scotsman that ever lived rang no bell.
 He nevertheless straightened his back and breathed deeply when he tried
 to explain to Loui.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

William Wallace fought the English for the freedom of Scotland for over
 a dozen years.
 They killed his wife and family and in the end he was betrayed.
 He gave his all, William Wallace.
 Biggest set of stones ever.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Loui looked at Ethan in puzzlement as he uncorked the fine scotch, its smoky
 aroma wafting upwards, arousing the senses.
 His question seemed to flatten Ethan's face right at the moment his nostrils
 had become so excited:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

But Scotland isn't free.
 You serve the Queen of England.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

That's not entirely true, I serve the Queen of the United Kingdom.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

But there's no Queen of the Scots, is there?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

She's also Queen of the Scots.
 And the Welsh.
 And the Irish.
 Well, at least some of the Irish.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

See, that's not unlike the situation here in Nigeria.
 The Igbo are like the Scots, they want to be free.
 Shouldn't they be free?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I don't have a say in that.
 It's not my job, and it's not my people.
 If they can, they will.
 And if you want to know, my father might have been born in Glasgow but
 I grew up in Kensington, so piss off with the Scots and all that.
 Pour, for the love of God.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Louis smiled wryly before he retorted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You brought it up, Captain.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan was starting to get properly wound up when the door bell rang and
 attracted his attention.
 He looked up from his drink and saw Louis pointing with his long bony index
 finger to a sturdy, tall and fit black man dressed in fatigues, the beret
 of the Nigerian Marine Corps smartly adorning his head.
 The man's eyes peered vehemently through the haze and fog of the smoke
 and dust that seemed to always twirl lazily in the Metropolitaine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The soldier's gaze quickly settled on Ethan, who was spinning around on
 his barstool to look at the newcomer directly.
 He cracked a smile and gave a mocking half-salute to the burly man who
 - judging by his epaulets - appeared to be a brevet Major.
 The man did not seem to share the same good humor and did not salute, neither
 did he seem to enjoy smiles and levity a lot.
 As he approached the bar, Ethan's mood had swung again towards his sweet
 side and he cheerfully made a gesture at the still open cupboard full of
 Littlemill, greeting the man with a proposition:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

James, this is a once in a lifetime chance for a once in a lifetime experience.
 It's Littlemill.
 It's the nectar of the Gods.
 It'll be monumental James; getting plastered with the finest scotch in
 the whole country, with little doubt.
 So, what is the unhappy occassion of your visit here in uniform? Tell me
 all about it so I can forget it with the help of Louis and Littlemill.
 Is it remotely serious? Are the Biafrans hurtling shells at Lagos? Can
 I go home now?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heavily set man had a quite intimidating appearance.
 The capability of severely wounding a man armed with nothing but his hands
 was the usual first impression.
 At odds with his brutal image he had a strangely calm and serene demeanor,
 a grim look on his face that implied his mind was occupied with grave matters.
 He approached Ethan and taking off his beret he calmly said:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's your brother, Ethan.
 We have reports their caravan was probably attacked today.
 Somewhere in the jungle near the border.
 They never reached Owerri.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan's smile evaporated.
 He suddenly looked somber and withdrawn.
 The news were a mood killer to say the least.
 He looked at James with wary, stern eyes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Red Cross is supposed to have Army support.
 Where was their support, James?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James' bulky shoulders shook with a disarmingly vulnerable shrug.
 He embraced Ethan with a single arm and told him in a friendly, casual
 manner:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Let's have a drink, Ethan.
 Let's talk.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


