 Used to drag me along.
 The bad leg is just a reminder.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James seemed to stiffen suddenly.
 He straightened his back before reaching for his glass, his voice a bit
 shallow and distant:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Which is worse, Ethan? The memories, or the leg?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ethan smiled while trying to down the last mouthful of Cullogh from his
 glass, and pointed to his mouth.
 When he did swallow it, his face contorted from the intense feeling of
 a wet fireball going down to his belly, but managed to respond in a timely
 manner:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Kenya, right.
 Nineteen sixty one.
 My squad had shipped out to Kenya as part of a counter-insurgency operation.
 The plan was to turn the various guerilla parties on each other, feeding
 disinformation and using scare tactics.
 We were supposed to make contact with a few loyalist bands, and organize
 a small force that would stop the insurrection in its heart.
 It was pretty complex, far-fetched and too optimistic.
 Very few men.
 No small wonder it failed.
 Of course that's not why we lost Kenya.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ethan stopped for a moment when Loui came with James' new glass of wine.
 He picked up Ethan's empty glass and nodded with a wink, before leaving
 them alone once again.
 Somewhere in the opposite corner of the Metropolitaine a loud crashing
 noise was heard and Ethans fleeting gaze revealed the bunch of sailors
 strewn around over lots of broken glasses and a couple of upturned tables.
 A loud chorus of laughters was heard and once the noise resumed its regularly
 high levels, Ethan decided to go on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We were trying to rendezvous with a loyalist cell in the Ript Valley, scout
 out the area, evaluate targets and then organize a strike to disorganize
 and demoralise the local rebel cells.
 Guerilla warfare textbook case.
 Anyway, first couple of nights in the jungle, all fine and dandy; nothing
 but mosquitoes, fucking jungle weather and bad sleep, which was to be expected
 in the bloody jungle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
On the third night though, I woke up not with a kick in the me bollocks.
 I realise my hands are all tied up.
 Can't fucking believe what's going on; whole squad captured like a bunch
 of campers.
 The sentries were talking about the last fucking Millwall-Chelsea game.
 Long story short, we got caught with our pants down.
 They didn't kill us outright, that would have been stupid and of no use.
 The Kenyans needed leverage, public approval, anything that would convince
 the parliament to say `balls off with Kenya, it's not worth it'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We were eleven men on that squad.
 At first I thought they would exchange us, but then we noticed we were
 going around in circles somewhere near Lake Rudolf, nothing like a plan.
 Like a long range patrol or whatnot.
 Our heavy gunner, McKinley, tried to make a run for it one day.
 He stumbled and tripped, dropped twenty feet down a cliff and broke both
 his legs.
 Their leader, a big brute of a man, shot him in the back of the head.
 Even said he was being merciful.
 That was when fucking bells started ringing in our heads.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
That cunt had it coming for him.
 We decided to have a go at them all together.
 We stopped for fresh water by a small river one day.
 While they were bathing, we ganged up on two of our guards.
 That's when I got stabbed in the knee and tore up the ligaments.
 Nobody died though.
 Except that man.
 I drowned that fucker.
 Held him down in the river till my hands turned blue and I couldn't feel
 them.
 First time I killed a man with my bare hands.
 We then hiked back through the jungle, the Kenyan's in tow.
 Debriefing them gave some insight into the area, but a fat lot of good
 that did in the end.
 I got a demerit for losing McKinley and getting captured.
 Should've been a major by now.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's the memories alright.
 Hadn't seen him in four years.
 Rarely called.
 Never wrote.
 He must've thought I couldn't care less.
 But it's the job, you know? The distance.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James interjected mildly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The scotch too?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan drained his glass, as if a real thirst was driving him and answered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
