Ethan shrugged indifferently, effortlessly shooting down Ludwig's hopes.
 A prolonged silence followed once again, regularly interrupted by the creaks
 and croans of the Land Rover's chassis.
 As the evening wore by, flies began to give their place to mosquitoes.
 The grassy hills rushed by, lush with vegetation, filled with tall, thin
 trees and distant mangroves.
 The swampy savannah drew distant with every passing minute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan turned and addressed Olufemi in Yoruba with a ghastly accent, but
 decent enough to be understood.
 The driver suddenly burst into laughter and started talking vividly with
 Ethan.
 A torrential flow of Yoruba was intermixed with laughs, giggles and extravagant
 hand gestures.
 Ethan was responding in kind, and judging by his tone, sometimes asking,
 sometimes filling in and sometimes simply nodding.
 Olufemi even made eye contact with Ludwig once, before breaking down in
 laughter once more before finally being able to settle down to his invariably
 dull and sullen mood.
 Ludwig looked at Ethan with eyes that shone rather irregularly and a voice
 slightly reminiscent of gritted teeth:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Care to share, Richard?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last word sounded unusually venomous for the good doctor.
 Ethan countered the doctor's irate mood with a radiating smile.
 He explained:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

He thinks you talk too much.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig raised his brow and nodded, right before instinctively slapping his
 arm, failing to kill a mosquito.
 Before Ludwig could have had the chance to retort in a manner unbecoming
 of a doctor, Olufemi suddenly cut in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For a doctor.
 We dem almost there.
 See now, the clearing.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both of them looked up ahead to where the road steered off course and into
 a dirt path that seemed to lead slowly upwards onto a small ridge.
 Ludwig asked then with barely conceiled exhilaration:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Is that where we stop for the night?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi gave a nod instead of answering properly, while Ethan was looking
 more and more at the sky, its rosy and purple hues lighting up the gathering
 clouds, dressing them in the imagery of cotton candy.
 While the last light could be seen falling around them, Ethan said with
 some disappointment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's going to rain like the devil, that's for sure.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The driver nodded his silent agreement, while Ludwig said with the slightest
 hint of irony:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I thought Brits liked rain.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To which Ethan commented wryly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We like rain alright.
 It's all that water we could live without.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi started laughing again, and this time Ludwig managed to crack a
 smile.
 Ethan laid back on his sack once more while the first droplets of water
 gathered on the windshield.
 Ludwig retorted with a grin:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

And the rest of us could be spared your dry sense of humor as well.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan lit up a cigarette and inhaled deeply before answering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Well said.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As Ludwig joined him, the small droplets rapidly grew into a proper tropical
 storm, causing even Olufemi to exclaim:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dis dey proper fuck.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan was about to translate when Ludwig made himself heard over the din
 of the storm:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I think I get the idea, Richard.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visibility had been reduced to the car up ahead, and only thanks to the
 powerful headlights.
 The caravan was moving with a walking speed, carefully treading on a dirt-turne
d-into-mud path barely wide enough to call a road.
 Olufemi made some colourful remarks about the driving conditions, to which
 Ethan remarked they should be happy they weren't being shot at.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig stabbed Ethan with a gaze unusually hard and firm for such a seemingly
 light-mannered man and asked him:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Would it make good press?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan shrugged and before he had time to answer, a blinding flash lit the
 area in front of them and in the blink of an eye they felt the surging
 overpressure of a shockwave on their eardrums.
 A wall of dirt and mud seemed to go up in the air, lifting with it the
 chassis of the Rover in front of the column.
 Ethan's shouting was barely heard through buzzing eardrums:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Landmine! Stop, stop! Get out, now!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi panicked and let go of the wheel, their car bumping on the Rover
 in front.
 The flaming debris of the destroyed Land Rover could be seen, lying on
 the edge of the road upturned and torn.
 Pandemonium ensued.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What was that?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Ludwig asked with a slight tremor in his voice.
 The answer from Ethan came accompanied by a powerful shove:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Landmine or RPG! Now move! Out of the car! And stay low!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi was faster to comply, opening his door and rushing out, frantically
 searching for more flashes or explosions, but none came.
 Ludwig sloppily made his way out of the doors in the back of the Rover
 over the assorted bags and crates, while Ethan opened the window behind
 him and drew himself out in a fluid motion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He shouted to the bewildered people in the caravan, some of which had already
 stepped outside their Rovers, dazed and confused:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Get out! Lay low and don't move!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan's eyes were frantically looking for signs of movement in the torrential
 rain, the light from the headlamps the only source of illumination.
 There were no muzzle flashes, launch trails or smoke.
 Lots of shouting and confusion, but the characteristic hammering sound
 of AKs was absent.
 This was not an ambush.
 Ethan's voice took on an authoritative yet calming tone:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Calm down.
 Stay put.
 No-one's shooting at us.
 It was a landmine.
 Tell the people next to you to calm down and stay put.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Everyone was drenched to the bone.
 All around him, Ethan could see faces frozen in sheer terror, some of them
 shaking visibly.
 Olufemi had started shouting calls to the other drivers in Yoruba, when
 Ethan's instincts kicked in; he quickly walked over him and put a hand
 to his mouth.
 Olufemi was surprised and looked at Ethan sideways, giving him a look of
 frustrated fear.
 Ethan put one finger to his mouth while shaking his head, and let go of
 Olufemi's mouth:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No shouting, not in Yoruba.
 Understand, mate? Not around these parts.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi could only nod.
 Rather baffled though he was, he motioned with his hands to the other drivers
 who by now had his attention to `lay low'.
 With fear and hesitation as plentiful as the rain pouring down on them,
 the drivers complied, some of them already on their knees and praying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan felt the heavy rain on his head, tried to wash away everything else
 and focus on the moment.
 He needed to calmly tell these people what to do next, when Ludwig came
 up from behind him, the sound of his approach muffled by the rain and the
 din from the people in shock.
 Ethan's eye simply caught a shadow approaching.
 He twisted around sharply, grabbed Ludwig from one arm and place his foot
 to act as a pivot.
 Before having time to actually see Ludwig, he was already throwing him
 down to the dirt, still grabbing his arm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig splashed in the mud yelling, markedly scared and half-witted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's me! It's me! Scheisse!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan breathed deeply, letting some of the adrenaline wear off before picking
 up Ludwig and offering his apologies:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sorry I jumped on you.
 It's a conditioned reflex.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig could not help but shout irately:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Conditioned reflex?!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Just so happens, yes.
 Never mind that, we need to get these people off the road.
 Someone fucked up the itinerary.
 Olufemi!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The driver turned and nodded.
 He looked shaken but he was evidently quick about his wits.
 Ethan leaned slightly towards him, shouting to be heard and pointing at
 the column of stopped rovers and the frightened crowd:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Step on the Rovers' tracks.
 Tell the rest of the drivers to get the people back inside.
 See if anyone's wounded, get the doctors working on them.
 We'll be safe as houses then.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olufemi nodded and carefully started walking towards the first Rover, while
 the people were shouting out questions to noone in particular.
 Ethan started walking up the front of the column, carefully passing by
 people and telling everyone to be calm and emphasize that they were probably
 safe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once he reached the debris of the first Rover, he saw the people in the
 second car frozen still.
 They had bled out of their ears, probably deaf and scared to death.
 Ethan took a closer look: the driver was still clutching his wheel, all
 tensed up and in shock.
 The explosion had shattered the windshield, and along the water that had
 pooled inside there was what remained of a shattered, blown away arm.
 The driver had shattered fragments of glass all over his face, and his
 eyes were a bloody mess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan shouted to Ludwig:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Ludwig! Grab a first aid kit, and come up front! Face injury! Try and stay
 on the tire tracks!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig nodded affirmatively and disappeared in the back of the Rover.
 Ethan grabbed the blind man from one arm and told him nothing.
 He simply squeezed him gently and felt the man's blood pumping like a flooded
 river.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once Ludwig arrived he shot a quick glance at the blown up vehicle, and
 quickly turned to say something to Ethan who shook his head in denial:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Not a chance, mate.
 I'm sorry.
 Enough explosives to throw five thousand pounds six feet in the air.
 It's a bloody miracle this one's lost just his eyes instead of his head.
 The others are in the back, scared shitless, a bit deaf probably but otherwise
 in one piece.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig nodded appreciatively and focused on the task at hand, trying not
 to think about the people in that first Rover.
 His motions were calm and professional, as if he was working in an examination
 room.
 Ethan urged him to hurry up, and took a few steps forward towards the small
 crater which had effortlessly turned into a pool.
 He took out a flashlight from one of his pants' pockets and a large leaf-shaped
 knife from an ankle belt.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He crouched and slowly crept towards the pool, carefully studying the ground,
 digging in with the knife at seemingly random intervals.
 Going past the pool, his eyes avidly scanned the mud.
 Before long, even under the unabating rain and all the mess of debris he
 caught a glimpse of a dull olive-green shape barely protruding from the
 muddy ground.
 A careful prod at the rim with the knife let him know this was another
 landmine.
 A few feet to his right, he could make out the outline of another.
 A slow, careful sweep with the flashlight uncovered two more, less than
 ten feet apart.
 He slid back to the crater and got up, jogging back to Ludwig and the injured
 man.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A certain amount of quiet and calm had started to settle among the crowd.
 Olufemi could be seen quietly exchanging concerned looks with the other
 drivers, some of them already back inside their Rovers, trying to find
 a dry smoke.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's a proper god-awful minefield,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said Ethan to Ludwig.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig was still dressing the eyes of the driver, after having administered
 some sedatives for the excruciating pain that would follow the end of the
 adrenaline rush.
 He was dripping wet, smeared with blood all over his hands and shirt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Your deductive reasoning amazes me,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said the doctor, not bothering to hide the tone of irony.
 Ethan replied calmly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It could have been a single land mine, an old ambush site.
 No, this was a proper minefield, there's probably more of them around the
 bushes and trees.
 We need to go back.
 I don't know who decided on this itinerary, but it wasn't safe.
 Killed those people in the Rover, and it might have killed us all.
 Might still as well.
 We need to get moving out of here.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig suddenly stopped tending to the wounded driver.
 He closed his eyes and seemed to whisper something in German.
 Ethan told him sternly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What are you blabbering about? They're dead, Ludwig.
 Come on now, pull it together.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The doctor exploded with fury at Ethan, letting his utensils drop to the
