 Detached? I mean, they were..
 Jesus, Richard.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan gave the doctor a long hard stare.
 His eyes seemed to waver a little, while his visage remained stern and
 grave-looking.
 His voice was pitched lower than usual:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It happens after a while, doctor.
 It keeps me sane, it keeps me alive.
 It's not something to be proud of, but that's just as human as curling
 up in a corner and crying, blaming yourself or others.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another thunder reverberated inside the small chamber, the small flame in
 the oil lamp on the shelf trembling in tune.
 Ludwig put out his cigarette and took off his glasses.
 He reached into his pockets and produced a small piece of clean linen with
 which he started cleaning his glasses.
 Ethan started to say something when the doctor spoke to him without meeting
 his gaze:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It seems you have everything worked out.
 You know your way around people dying, dealing with traumatic disorders
 and guilt.
 So tell me, please, is it normal if I feel like punching you in the face?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan paused for a moment, and shrugged almost apologetically.
 He replied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If you think it'll make you feel better, then by all means.
 I'm not your problem though.
 You're still emotional from what happened, and that's just --
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ludwig's fist connected with Ethans cheekbone and stopped him mid-sentence.
 Before he slammed the frail door behind him as he left the room, Ludwig
 shouted in a fit of rage:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Emotional?! What would you know about emotions?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan was caught off-guard, but recovered quickly enough.
 He rushed outside the small guestroom and onto an ill-lit corridor.
 Even as he started off to follow the doctor, a figure suddenly appeared
 to be blocking his way.
 He stopped and looked genuinely surprised when he saw a tall, slender woman
 sporting a look that could have bored a hole in his face.
 Subdued light poured off a small opening to her right.
 She was still holding the tattered curtain that served as a door when she
 sternly told Ethan:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

For God's sake, be quiet!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I'm sorry about the noise and all, sister but it really is none of your
 business so --
