\begin_layout Chapter
Dead men can't dance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The old man drained the last of the beer off the keg, and brought the bottle
 to Ethan's small table.
 There was some beer foam right at the mouth of the bottle, which the old
 man blew away with a whizzy puff, before settling it down on the table.
 He then looked at Ethan with wide, almost hazy, glassy eyes and said:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

He can smell you are trouble.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan shook his head and his stilted smile had the look of tasting salt
 about it.
 He drank another gulp of beer and asked the old man, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

I didn't know trouble has a smell of its own,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 trying to sound non-chalant, unconvincingly enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It doesn't.
 It's the smell of shit!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 blared the owner with an almost accusing stare and suddenly broke down
 in laughter.
 The other two men followed suit, showing off hollowed out mouths and wrinkled,
 leathery faces worn through a life-time of being used to hardships of all
 kinds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

And you're full of it, Englishman.
 Who dem asking for trouble, days like these, but dem trouble, no?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 said one of the two, while the owner chimed in himself again, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You can't hide a pile of shit if you paint it gold, mister.
 It still smells, so do you.
 Your man, whoever he is, won't be coming.
 Hope he didn't take your money first.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ethan couldn't manage a reply.
 Taken by surprise by their straightforward manner, he barely managed a
 grin while acceding to having being played like a fool:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

He did.
 I'm that transparent, am I?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 he said, while all three men smiled and nodded.
 The one who hadn't even spoken a word said then, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

You dem English
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 smiled, shrugged and sipped his beer.
 The owner was sitting behind his counter, and tapping his hand with each
 word he said to Ethan, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What's a white man doing in the middle of a war?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and added with a rather grim face, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

