\begin_layout Standard
The morgue's pale blue-white neon lights made even the living stand out
 as if they had been just as cold dead as the corpses filling it.
 The whole cooling chamber was actually reserved for important people, like
 officials, dignitaries, and mostly foreigners.
 Somehow to the Biafrans it was really important that a dead foreigner -
 perhaps a journalist or a UN official or a priest with inordinate amounts
 of belief in mankind - received all due care when the time came: a morgue,
 a funeral, a tombstone.
 The rest of the normal people could just die wherever they liked, but not
 the foreigners.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

