\begin_layout Standard
* * *
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James was sitting at his office, his shoulders tense from impatience.
 At a corner of his desk, sat an empty glass jag, filled with sagged, dried
 out lemons; it had been sitting there for days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He threw cursive glances at the phone, as if he was trying to make it ring.
 When it did though, the voices of the men that talked to him rang hollow
 in his ears.
 He rarely answered in anything other than a curt, official tone; he could
 hardly remember what had been going on around Headquarters for the past
 couple of days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There were reports and briefings, both from the British and their own intelligen
ce branch; there were troop assessments and updated maps, but there was
 nothing very intelligent about them.
 Whatever Lagos thought about the war had little to do with the war itself;
 and those on the front had little idea of what they were actually doing,
 other than pushing forward, shooting everything that moved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But that was just hazy imagery in James' mind's eye; what he longed and
 waited for wasn't in those reports.
 He was waiting for a phone call that never seemed to come.
 It had been days since Ethan had left; no contact whatsoever.
 It was a feat in itself keeping him loosely tracked by filling in the gaps
 from all the reports he could get his hands on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He'd reached Owerri for sure, that much he knew; it wasn't hard to find
 an Englishman, even amongst all the chaos and death.
 Especially when he made such dramatic appearances like the one in Onitsha.
 He didn't expect him to have it in him; and there was no real chance the
 incident at the bar wasn't Ethan's handiwork.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It had began to take shape; everything was coming together nicely.
 All those years before, he could have never expected things to turn out
 that way; he had never expected fate to turn the cards in his favor.
 If only Enkele was still alive, he would taste the changing age, and know
 that it wasn't all for naught.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
The white elephant's days are over
\shape default
, thought James.
 
\shape italic
It's our turn now, brother
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He had stopped the ceiling fan; the window blinds were closed but still
 the heat was almost unbearable.
 Sweat ran down his forehead and his cheeks.
 It touched his lips and he tasted it; it was sour and salty, with a hint
 of bitterness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
It must be all those lemons in the tea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The phone rang and James heartbeat went racing.
 He looked at the telephone in awe, as if it was a thing of magic, a powerful
 beast in hiding.
 It rang twice more before James snapped out of his stupor and picked up
 the receiver hesitantly.
 A voice on the other end reported name and rank curtly, and added in Yoruba:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

There's an outside line for you, sir.
 The number is not registered, would you like me to record?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No, that will be fine sergeant.
 Patch me through, and resume your duties.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Very well, sir,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 replied the sergeant and after a short series of buzzing and clicking sounds,
 the voice of an older man came on.
 He spoke English with a frail, nasal tone, as if every word required an
 effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It's time, James.
 Do what you must.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
