\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And that was when Ethan sprang at him, swiveling his torso sideways.
 James' gun went off with a clamor, but Ethan was already pushing the gun
 away with one hand and aiming for his neck with the other.
 James' gaze went wild as he realised he had missed, but it curiously enough
 settled the next moment in a calm, peaceful stare; his carotis was shattered
 and he was drowning in his own blood.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
James fell face down in the mud, the colour of blood lost in the reddish
 brown mud.
 Ethan took a moment, sighed and looked at James body with a peculiar mix
 of disdain, surprise and sadness.
 He then took another look at his brother's body, and saw his vacant stare
 as rain kept falling on him.
 He sat down in the mud, and began to cry as if the rain that fell from
 above burned him.
 After a few more minutes, he came to grips and quietened down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He took a deep, long breath and looked at the bodies once more.
 He saw the helicopter idly sitting by, and started laughing and crying,
 without being able to control either feeling; he felt he had finally let
 go of himself.
 He didn't know how to fly; he suddenly realised he was still alive and
 couldn't stop laughing at the absurdness of it all.
\end_layout

